## Practical Learnings

- Bright pages need dark keylines or white contour borders on sprites
- Encounter stagger prevents noisy timer overlap
- BLACKOUT was too aggressive — softer BLUR replaced it; COOLDOWN/LURE too abstract — removed
- All scores multiples of 10 for cleaner display and mental math
- Near-miss is more fun as pure visual feedback without score
- Toasts should show actual amounts ("+40") not encoded labels ("R-BON+40")
- Game settings (sound, vehicle) should be global, not per-tab
- Extension popup should be static HTML — no JS build step needed
- Adaptive shadow (module-level lightness) is simpler than per-sprite surface sampling
- `scrollbar-gutter: stable` is cleaner than manual paddingRight compensation
- Daily modifier as persistent HUD label beats a run-start toast
- Center-biased spawn gives better first impression than bottom-biased
- Single overgrowth ladder (grass → bush → tree) is clearer than two-kind × three-stage matrix
- Distinct shapes per special polarity aids split-second pickup decisions
- Popup/HUD style parity needs deliberate alignment across canvas and HTML surfaces
- SVG text elements render inconsistently across tools — use SVG rect paths for pixel-art wordmarks
- `rsvg-convert` renders SVGs correctly; `sips` silently drops text/gradients/patterns
- Code audits catch orphaned config values that accumulate across phases
- Store listing docs rot fast — audit with every major phase
- Police helicopter is a clean late-game escalation via PoliceChaseState variant field
- Train encounters are novel — expanded rail detection (CSS borders, thin dividers) dramatically increased page coverage beyond initial ~15-25%
- Sprite showcase sound test panel needs force-enable of AudioManager (bypass user's sound toggle)

## Success Criteria

A good run should feel like:
- early: clean, readable, inviting
- mid: routing decisions, specials, rising police pressure
- late: overgrown map, tighter routes, high-score tension
- failure: stylish and readable, immediate desire to retry
